    "millsfield:images_texts": [
      "MEET\nSAN FRANCICO\nMEET\nSAN FRANCIS CO\nCompliments of UNITED AIR LINES",
      "GOING...\nNORTH? EAST? SOUTH?\nIT'S THRIFTY TO FLY UNITED\nYou save many hours of valuable time-and costs\nare comparable with first class surface travel!\nTHEN you are ready to leave San\nFrancisco, remember this:\nUnited Air Lines offers fast, fre-\nquent transportation in any direc-\ntion you want to go... north, south,\nor east!\nAnd the economy of United's lux-\nurious air travel will surprise you.\nFor instance, suppose you're plan-\nning to visit the other great fair.\nFrom here to New York, United's\nfare is only $149.95-with 10% off\non round trips. And that includes\neverything, even meals aloft. Tips\naren't accepted.\n****\nGoing north, south or east, flying\nin a United Mainliner is the quick-\nest, most convenient way to travel.\nIn planning your trip-first call\nDOuglas 1681 and find out how\nlittle it will cost you to fly United!\nTickets and information: 400 Post St.,\nSan Francisco; telephone DOuglas 1681.\nOr Travel Bureaus, Hotels, Telegraph Offices.\nUNITED AIR LINES\nThe Main Line Airway\nMORE THAN A ROUTE...A STANDARD OF SERVICE",
      "Treasure Island within the Golden Gate-Berkeley in foreground—San Francisco-Oakland Transbay Bridge on left\nMEET SAN FRANCISCO\nWith Mary Hampton\nI IS not merely the clanging little cable cars and the sidewalk stands of vivid flowers that makes\nSan Francisco different from any other city in the world. San Francisco is a city apart—with a per-\nsonality as vivid and accidental as a scaramouche's. Like Topsy, it just growed, out of the strangest\nmixture of gentle Mission fathers and Spanish adventurers, out of gentlemen from the old\nsouth and madmen from across all the seas, rushing in with gun and shovel at the cry of gold. It\ngrew out of the keen-eyed shop-keepers and the rouged tarts, out of famous European chefs and\nquick Chinese who came swarming at the heels of those who unearthed the gold. Suddenly, therefore, the\nearly little Yerba Buena outgrew its bounds. It began to push out over the hills—over all fourteen of them\nfinally—until the whole peninsula between bay and Pacific was covered with a new city. That is San Fran-\ncisco today.\nMany prospectors found themselves millionaires over night. So to them and their bags of gold came\ntrekking, quickly enough, comforts to be sold, and luxuries to be bartered for a bag of gold. It was then that\nthe world-and San Francisco—noticed that it happened to sit beside one of the three greatest, natural\nharbors in the world. The rest just happened.\nWith their quick gold these hordes of rich adventurers early developed a fabulous standard of living-\nall easy-come and easy-go. They spent their gold and shot their guns and drank their straight whiskey with\nstory-book abandon. And they loved as best they could, for women were extremely scarce. Perhaps for\nthis reason too, there was a sky-high premium on entertainment. Audiences poured out a personal apprecia-"
    ],
